        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Magistratus Romani, pro Reip[ublicae] utilitate; non pro dignitate privatarum personarum. pro se quisq[ue]: et qui non possunt esse 
                        foris Scipiones, domi esse volunt Petilij: audentes eos vexare cavillando, quos non audent ben&egrave; merendo a[e]mulari.
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Scipio Aemilianus"/> <!-- LS, right one? or referring to all of them?! -->
                <person name="Quintus Petillius Cerialis"/> <!-- I added this one -->
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                The Roman offices served the use of the republic, not the grandeur of individual persons. Every one for himself, and those who cannot be 
                Scipios abroad, want to be Petiliuses at home. And they have the nerve to taunt those by quibbling who they do not dare to rival by deserving 
                well.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Ingrata Scipionibus Roma: nec aedificant Africani, et Asiatici gloriosa cognomina, sine altioribus, firmioribusq[ue] fundamentis 
                        stabilitae magnitudinis. Licuisset Scipionibus esse potentioribus, si suu[m] statu[m] privatis opibus, publicisq[ue] amicitiis valide 
                        fundatum, qua possent Auctoritate munivissent. Deficiunt homines, nisi cogantur vinculis, aut teneantur beneficijs. 
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Scipio Aemilianus"/> <!-- LS, is he referring to all of them? should I tag them all? -->
                    <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                    <person name="Lucius Cornelius Scipio Asiaticus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Rome is ungrateful to the Scipios; but the Africanuses and Asiaticuses do not create their illustrious eponyms without very deep and steady 
                foundations of firmly established greatness. The Scipios could have been more powerful, if they had buttressed their position, based strongly 
                on private means and public relations, as much as they could with authority. People defect, unless they are forced by chains or kept by 
                favours.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Disciplinae militaris solidus validusq[ue] usus in Rep[ublica]. Duros dura faciunt: molles mollia. Assuescere oportet invictos: 
                        nec unq[uam] languescere. <!-- LS, there's something that looks like a pi sign. I'm assuming it's part of unq[uam] -->
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                The firm and powerful use of military training in the Republic. Hard measures make hard men; soft ones make soft men. It is right for the 
                invincible to get used to it and never to grow weak.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
